<DOC><DOCNO> AP881018-0028 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0131EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Obit-SuspendedAnimation     10-18 0181</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Obit-Suspended Animation,0186</SECOND><HEAD>Woman Who Was Put In Coma Dies</HEAD><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A 76-year-old woman who had been in a comasince surgeons placed her in ``suspended animation'' six week agoto remove an egg-sized aneurysm near her brain has died.   Cecilia Duffy of Pittsburgh died Monday, hours after she wastransferred to D.T. Watson Rehabilitation Hospital for therapy.   She suffered cardio-pulmonary arrest, said John Righettispokesman at the suburban hospital.   Duffy had been listed in fair condition before being transferredfrom Allegheny General Hospital, said Allegheny General spokeswomanKaren Long.   Surgeons at Allegheny General put Duffy in a coma Aug. 31 andstopped her heart 51 minutes so they could remove the aneurysm.   During the operation, doctors reduced her body temperature by 40degrees, drained her blood and placed her in ``suspendedanimation,'' which lets surgeons cure high-risk aneurysms onceconsidered inoperable.   Doctors said Duffy opened her eyes in late September for thefirst time after the operation. She was transferred to D.T. Watsonso she could begin undergoing rehabilitative therapy designed tohelp the injured brain heal.</TEXT></DOC>